# Architecture and Layering Rules

## Dependency direction — one way only

```text
Handler/Controller
    ↓ (calls)
Service / Use Case
    ↓ (calls)
Repository / Store
    ↓ (calls)
Infrastructure (DB, Redis, gRPC)
```

A lower layer must never import or depend on a higher layer. Violations are detected by `go-arch-lint` in CI.

```go
// WRONG — store calls service; inverts dependency
package store

import "github.com/Rick1330/ibex-harness/services/auth/internal/service"

func (s *AgentStore) GetAndValidate(...) {
    service.ValidatePermissions(...) // store calling service!
}

// RIGHT — store only touches database; service composes store + validation
package store
// No import of service package
func (s *AgentStore) GetByIDAndOrg(...) (*AgentRecord, error) { ... } // pure DB access

package service
import "store"
func (s *AgentService) GetVerifiedAgent(ctx, orgID, agentID) (*AgentRecord, error) {
    record, err := s.store.GetByIDAndOrg(ctx, orgID, agentID)
    if err != nil { return nil, err }
    if record == nil { return nil, ErrAgentNotAuthorized }
    return record, nil
}
```

## No business logic in handlers

Handlers (HTTP, gRPC) do exactly four things:
1. Parse and validate input
2. Extract auth context (org_id, permissions) from middleware
3. Call one service function
4. Serialize and write the response

```go
// WRONG — business logic in handler
func (h *Handler) CreateToken(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    // ...
    if len(req.Name) == 0 { // ← validation belongs in service/request type
        ...
    }
    hash := argon2.Hash(token) // ← business logic in handler
    _, err := h.db.Exec(ctx, "INSERT INTO tokens...") // ← direct DB access in handler!
}

// RIGHT — handler delegates completely
func (h *Handler) CreateToken(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    var req CreateTokenRequest
    if err := json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&req); err != nil {
        writeError(w, 400, "INVALID_JSON", err.Error()); return
    }
    orgID := middleware.OrgIDMust(r.Context())
    resp, err := h.tokenService.Create(r.Context(), orgID, req) // one service call
    if err != nil {
        writeServiceError(w, err); return
    }
    writeJSON(w, 201, resp)
}
```

## No direct database access from proxy service in Phase 1

The proxy service communicates with the database ONLY through the auth service gRPC API. It does not have its own `pgxpool.Pool`. This keeps the proxy stateless and eliminates a class of multi-master write issues.

```go
// WRONG — proxy has its own DB connection
func init() {
    proxyDB, _ = pgxpool.New(ctx, os.Getenv("DATABASE_URL"))
}

// RIGHT — proxy calls auth gRPC for all identity operations
// The proxy's only external connections are: Redis (rate limit + cache) + Auth gRPC
```

## Shared packages (`packages/*`) have no service-specific imports

A package in `packages/` must not import from `services/`. It is shared infrastructure. If it imports a service, it has become tightly coupled to that service's internals.

```go
// WRONG — packages/ratelimit imports from the proxy service
import "github.com/Rick1330/ibex-harness/services/proxy/internal/config"

// RIGHT — packages/* only import other packages/* or stdlib/external libraries
```
